1.description:
This is the first tutorial level and is not interactive.

The shape in the upper left corner is a Glider.

The rainbow square in the lower right is the Goal.

Click play and watch what happens.
1.name: Tutorial 1: Glider
1.win: When you win you will be graded. Congratulations on an A!

10.description:
Alright, it's time for your first real mission! Try to tear your way through the barrier and get to the Goal!

If your first attempt fails, remember that you can move something you build by a single unit, and the outcome can be completely different.

Also, notice how this level is limited to playing a maximum of 10 cells in the green playable zone!
10.name: CH1E2: Fanblades II
10.win: You'll often need to "jiggle" your drawings by a tile.

12.description:
This mission is a bit different than the ones you've played before. This time, instead of activating a goal, you're trying to NOT activate the blinking red Anti Goal!

To win, you must survive 50 generations without the Anti Goal activating.
12.lose: Try to cut off the glider and keep the Anti Goal from activating.
12.name: CH1E4: The Antigoal
12.win: Never let those pesky Anti Goals activate!

2.description:
Try to recreate that same Glider pattern you saw in the previous level by tapping on the field.

For your convenience, its pattern has been added to your Library.

You can only alter the state of cells within the green Playable Zones.
2.name: Tutorial 2: Build a Glider
2.win: The Glider is your new best friend!

3.description:
There's something in the way of your Goal!

If you draw a Glider in both boxes, one will destroy the barrier and the other will activate the Goal.
3.name: Tutorial 3: Build Two Gliders
3.win: Breaking barriers is a useful technique.

4.description:
Flip or rotate anything you draw to flip or rotate the outcome.



Tip: If you ever see multiple goals, you only need to activate one to win.
4.name: Tutorial 4: Symmetry
4.win: Remember, flipping and rotating objects will flip and rotate what they do!

47.description:
This one looks pretty difficult. You can't simply send a Spaceship up and crash it into the wall and spawn a Glider, as the horizontal gap is too small.

As a hint, I was able to beat this on Generation 432 with 20 Cells in Play.
47.name: Getting Difficult

48.description:
Other than a few Still Lifes protecting the Goal, this isn't too interesting of a level. Unless, you consider, that there is no line of sight between you and the Goal, and you may need to play off of two separate walls to reach the Goal.

This level was first beaten by @endeavourize with 18 Cells Played and 375 Generations.
48.name: Round the Bend

5.description: Make use of rotation to beat this level!
5.name: Tutorial 5: Flip your Glider

6.description:
This level has two Spaceships. Just like a Glider, a Spaceship can move across the playing field and retain its original shape.

Depending on a Spaceships distance from a wall, it will release a Glider either to the right or the left when it crashes.
6.name: Tutorial 6: Spaceship
6.win: Moving a spaceship 1 unit from a wall changes the glider direction.

7.description:
Using your newfound knowledge of Spaceships, try to activate the goal in this level.



Tip: Notice the red rectangle. This is called a Deadzone, no cells will survive inside of it. These will have the same effect as the edge of a map when something collides with it.
7.name: Tutorial 7: Build a Spaceship
7.win: Spaceships releasing Gliders can be very useful!

8.description:
This is the final level of the Tutorial.

The shape on this screen is called the Multum in Parvo.

Notice how something simple can become incredibly complex and seemingly unpredicable.
8.name: Tutorial 8: Chaos from Order
8.win: If a level is too big you can always pinch and zoom.

dictionary.confirm_reset: Are you SURE you would like to destroy all your progress and start over?
dictionary.how_to_play:
How to Play

Tap the arena in a green Playable Zone to toggle cells.

No cells can be alive in the red Dead Zones.

The rainbow tiles are Goal tiles and need to be activiated to beat levels.

Conway's Game of Life

The Game of Life is governed by the following four rules:

  1. Any live cell with fewer than two live neighbours dies.
  2. Any live cell with two or three live neighbours lives.
  3. Any live cell with more than three live neighbours dies.
  4. Any dead cell with exactly three live neighbours becomes a live cell.

If you're interested in learning more, read about Conway's Game of Life on WikiPedia.
